Chapter 5: Advanced Mechanics “We don’t have shields in our culture. It seems strange to my boy, I imagine. In our country, if you don’t want to get hit, you move out of the way.” Akaviri Potentate Versidue-Shaie, “2920, The Last Year of the First Era”

Combat Overview In most adventures there is conflict, and this conflict is often physical. After all, the world of Nirn can be a dangerous Combat encounters can be resolved by following these steps: place. Wars, strange monsters, criminals, mercenaries, and any number of other scenarios can all force a party to use violence Step 1: Determine Surprise to accomplish their goals, or simply force the party into dan- If one or more characters aren’t expecting an attack, or aware of gerous situations. This chapter contains mechanics for resolving their attacker’s intentions, they have been surprised. The GM combat, as well as other game mechanics to handle the variety of should determine which characters count as being surprised for situations the players might encounter during their adventures. the first round of combat. Surprised characters do not roll 1d6 for initiative; they simply use their Initiative Rating. They also A Note on Time may only take reactions until after their first Turn has passed. The UESRPG divides time into two categories: narrative time and structured time. Narrative Time is meant to be used in Step 2: Set the Scene any situations that do not demand the time-sensitive resolution Before the characters can begin taking their turns, the GM of tasks. Functionally this means that almost any non-combat should outline the parts of the scenario that they are aware of, situation will use narrative time. In game terms, narrative time including the combatants they face, the positions of everyone is a period in which the GM can freely advance time at any rate involved, and the environment they’re fighting in. If the group based on the needs of the story and the players. This could mean is using a battle map or grid, this would be the time to set it up! briefly describing the party’s long journey across a vast desert, or playing out an important conversation minute by minute. Step 3: Determine Initiative To determine the order in which characters take their tu