• Mounted characters can evade ranged attacks but only while If the target is protected by cover that the attack can penetrate
moving. They cannot evade melee attacks (except those with relative ease, the attacker suffers no penalty to hit but rolls from other mounted characters), though their mount can. twice and chooses the lower value for damage.
• Mounted characters may parry or Counter-Attack in
response to attacks against their mount.
• Mounted characters use their mount’s Speed.
• The GM may rule that ranged attacks that miss the char-
acter or their mount hit the other target instead. 103

Improvised Weaponry In certain cases a character might find themselves forced to fight using improvised weaponry. Attacks with improvised weapons suffer the usual -20 untrained penalty unless the character’s Combat Style includes improvised weapons. The table below provides a set of guidelines for the GM. Improvised Weaponry Guidelines Type Damage Range Tiny 1d4 1m (gain Small quality) Small 1d6 1m Medium 1d8 2m Large 1d10 3m Huge 1d12 4m The GM should feel free to give certain improvised weapons appropriate weapon qualities based on the type of object. Unarmed Combat Unarmed combat is when a character fights using their natural weapons. Characters are always capable of attempting to fight in this manner, even if they do not have unarmed combat as part of their Combat Style. Characters attempt a Combat Style test using Strength or Agility with the standard -20 penalty for Grappling using an untrained skill, if applicable. In place of making a normal attack a character can choose to attempt to grapple their opponent. This requires a Combat Style A character’s natural weapons use the profile specified below test (the style must include unarmed combat) opposed against unless the character has the Natural Weapons (*) trait (which either a Combat Style (with unarmed), Athletics, or Evade test. overrides the default profile). If a character has a Combat Style On success, the target gains the restrained condition. The target that includes unarmed combat, that skill can be used for attacks may attempt to escape by using the resist action. On success with the character’s natural weapons. Natural weapons ignore they break free. rules regarding one, two, or hand and a half weapons, and cannot be disarmed. Natural Weapons cannot be enchanted. Characters suffer a -30 penalty when attempting to grapple characters of larger size than them, and they cannot grapple Default Natural Weapon Profiles characters of two or more sizes larger. While they have an oppo- Type Damage Range nent restrained, the character may not move but may take the following actions (each is a primary action that costs 1 AP): Punches/Kicks 1d4 1m Claws 1d4; Slashing 1m
• T akedown: The character may render their victim, and
themself, prone. They suffer no prone penalties in relation Parrying/Counter-Attacking while Unarmed to any tests made against their target. If an unarmed combatant is facing an opponent with a weapon • Move: The character may move themself and their victim with a longer range and they are within their own engagement a number of meters up to their Strength bonus in any range, then they can attempt to parry that weapon’s attacks or direction. Counter-Attack. Otherewise melee attacks cannot be parried • A ttack: The character may make a normal attack against or countered by unarmed characters. their restrained victim, who cannot defend themself. They must use a weapon with a 1m range or less. If the target is both prone and restrained and the character is armed, this can be a coup de grâce. If the character is unarmed, then they can choose to instead cause the target to lose 1 Stamina point. 104

